/*

| Topic                      | Key Point                                           |
| -------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------- |
| Nesting                    | One function calls another function                 |
| Nested Function Definition | Not allowed in C                                    |
| Recursion                  | Function calls itself                               |
| Base Condition             | Stops recursion                                     |
| 1D Array                   | Pass only array name                                |
| 2D Array                   | Specify second dimension                            |
| Strings                    | Passed like character arrays                        |
| Automatic Variable         | Local, destroyed after function                     |
| Global Variable            | Available throughout the program                    |
| Static Variable            | Retains value between function calls                |
| Register Variable          | Stored in CPU register for faster access            |
| `extern`                   | Refers to a variable defined in another file        |
| Scope                      | Region where a variable is accessible               |
| Lifetime                   | Duration for which a variable exists                |
| Visibility                 | Whether a variable can be accessed in a given scope |









| **Term**                                 | **Simple Definition**                                                                                                |
| ---------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Arguments**                            | Values passed to a function to help it perform a specific task.                                                      |
| **Block Statement (Compound Statement)** | A group of statements enclosed within `{ }` braces.                                                                  |
| **Function**                             | A self-contained block of code that performs a specific task.                                                        |
| **Modular Programming**                  | A programming technique in which a large program is divided into smaller, independent modules (functions).           |
| **Calling Program (Calling Function)**   | The function that calls another function.                                                                            |
| **Called Function**                      | The function that is invoked (called) by another function.                                                           |
| **Function Body**                        | The part of a function enclosed in `{ }` that contains local variables and executable statements.                    |
| **Function Header**                      | The first line of a function containing the return type, function name, and parameter list.                          |
| **Function Type (Return Type)**          | Specifies the type of value that a function returns (e.g., `int`, `float`, `void`).                                  |
| **Parameter List**                       | A list of variables (formal parameters) that receive values from the calling function.                               |
| **Function Definition**                  | The complete implementation of a function, including its header and body.                                            |
| **Function Declaration (Prototype)**     | A statement that tells the compiler the function's name, return type, and parameters before it is used.              |
| **Function Call**                        | A statement that transfers control to a function to execute it.                                                      |
| **Formal Arguments (Formal Parameters)** | Variables declared in the function definition that receive values from the calling function.                         |
| **Actual Arguments (Actual Parameters)** | Values, variables, or expressions passed to a function during a function call.                                       |
| **Return Statement**                     | A statement that ends a function and optionally sends a value back to the calling function.                          |
| **Recursion**                            | A process in which a function calls itself until a base condition is reached.                                        |
| **Nesting of Functions**                 | A situation where one function calls another function.                                                               |
| **Nested Function Call**                 | A function call used as an argument of another function, e.g., `mul(mul(5,2),6)`.                                    |
| **External Variable (Global Variable)**  | A variable declared outside all functions and accessible throughout the program.                                     |
| **Local Variable (Automatic Variable)**  | A variable declared inside a function or block and accessible only within that function or block.                    |
| **Static Variable**                      | A variable that retains its value throughout the program even after the function ends.                               |
| **Register Variable**                    | A variable stored in a CPU register for faster access.                                                               |
| **Scope**                                | The region of a program where a variable or function can be accessed.                                                |
| **Visibility**                           | The ability of a program to access a variable within its scope.                                                      |
| **Lifetime (Longevity)**                 | The period during which a variable exists in memory during program execution.                                        |
| **Pass by Value**                        | A method where a copy of the actual argument is passed to the function; changes do not affect the original variable. |
| **Pass by Address**                      | A method where the address of a variable or array is passed to the function; changes affect the original data.       |
| **Prototype**                            | Another name for a function declaration.                                                                             |
| **Array Argument**                       | Passing an array name to a function so it can access all elements of the array.                                      |
| **String Argument**                      | Passing a character array (string) to a function.                                                                    |
| **Multifile Program**                    | A program whose source code is divided into multiple files and linked together during compilation.                   |
| **`extern` Keyword**                     | Declares that a variable or function is defined in another file or elsewhere in the program.                         |
| **`auto` Keyword**                       | Explicitly declares an automatic (local) variable.                                                                   |
| **`static` Keyword**                     | Makes a variable retain its value between function calls or limits the visibility of functions/variables to a file.  |
| **`register` Keyword**                   | Requests the compiler to store a variable in a CPU register for faster execution.                                    |






*/